As for the pain I named in that sonnet,
I meant this: looking back, I never knew
you lived in Brooklyn while I lived there too.
Yet doing out the math, I see you may
have even been there earlier than I.
And never once did I conceive the thought:
Patsy is here. I ought to ask her out,
invite her to this party, or for coffee.

That too proceeds from the original
absence. Although I saw you on Avenue D,
when twice you turned away, that motion pulled
our handshake under with it, and the rest.
The whole thing sank. It was impossible
to form the thought of you as someone there.

And then came that manifestation: you
were pointed out to me beneath the blue
churro hat, hiding there. But why from me?
And why that blotch of red upon your cheek
when I came near? What was that trauma then?
Whatever it was, it traumatized me too.

You said, “Yeah, but we’re going twice,” and left
with those two friends. I took the freight elevator
down when next it came, and called, “Hey, ladies!”
Then saw you three up ahead, moving slow,
that interesting angled walk you had,
some forty-five-degree riff off a glide.

I joined you. There was laughter. Then I tried
to put my arm around you—“Ah, Patsy!”—
and felt your center, strong beneath the play,
the way you resisted from the middle out.
I know what centers feel like. Aikido
has given me ten thousand in the body.
And yours was one of the strongest I have known.

Such persons, moving as you do, compel
an instant love that seems to come from nowhere.
It simply appears. I knew this once before
in Sensei Sugano, down on Eighteenth Street,
at New York Aikido. He had that same
nobility of motion on the mat.
I loved him for the way he walked onto it,
for how he crossed it, simply being there.

And when he died—though first they took his foot—
I learned what I had felt was not mine alone.
The others loved him too. That kind of form,
that way of moving through the given world,
draws love at once, as if the body knew
before the mind could say what it had found.

